# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: gtk-sharp
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:gtk-sharp/c-sharp-programming-language] The principal designers of the C# programming language were Anders Hejlsberg, Scott Wiltamuth, and Peter Golde from Microsoft.
[src:gtk-sharp/c-sharp-programming-language] It was first widely distributed in July 2000 and was later approved as an international standard by Ecma (ECMA-334) in 2002 and ISO/IEC (ISO/IEC 23270 and 20619) in 2003.
[src:gtk-sharp/c-sharp-programming-language] Microsoft introduced C# along with .NET Framework and Microsoft Visual Studio, both of which are, technically speaking, closed-source.
[src:gtk-sharp/c-sharp-programming-language] At the time, Microsoft had no open-source products.
[src:gtk-sharp/c-sharp-programming-language] Four years later, in 2004, a free and open-source project called Mono began, providing a cross-platform compiler and runtime environment for the C# programming language.
[src:gtk-sharp/c-sharp-programming-language] A decade later, Microsoft released Visual Studio Code (code editor), Roslyn (compiler), and the unified .NET platform (software framework), all of which support C# and are free, open-source, and cross-platform.
[src:gtk-sharp/c-sharp-programming-language] Mono also joined Microsoft, but was not merged into .NET.
[src:gtk-sharp/c-sharp-programming-language] As of November 2025, the most recent stable version of the language is C# 14.
[src:gtk-sharp/c-sharp-programming-language] During the development of the .NET Framework, the class libraries were originally written using a managed code compiler system named *Simple Managed C* (SMC).
[src:gtk-sharp/c-sharp-programming-language] In January 1999, Anders Hejlsberg formed a team to build a new language at the time called COOL, which stood for "C-like Object Oriented Language".
[src:gtk-sharp/c-sharp-programming-language] Microsoft had considered keeping the name "COOL(C-like Object Oriented Language)" as the final name of the language, but chose not to do so for trademark reasons.
[src:gtk-sharp/c-sharp-programming-language] By the time the .NET project was publicly announced at the July 2000 Professional Developers Conference, the language had been renamed C#, and the class libraries and ASP.NET runtime were ported to C#.
[src:gtk-sharp/c-sharp-programming-language] Hejlsberg was C#'s principal designer and lead architect at Microsoft, and had been previously involved with the design of Turbo Pascal, Embarcadero Delphi (formerly CodeGear Delphi, Inprise Delphi and Borland Delphi), and Visual J++.
[src:gtk-sharp/c-sharp-programming-language] In interviews and technical papers, he has stated that flaws in most major programming languages (e.g.
[src:gtk-sharp/c-sharp-programming-language] C++, Java, Delphi, and Smalltalk) drove the fundamentals of the Common Language Runtime (CLR), which, in turn, drove the design of the C# language.
[src:gtk-sharp/c-sharp-programming-language] In July 2000, Hejlsberg said that C# is "not a Java clone" and is "much closer to C++" in its design.
[src:gtk-sharp/c-sharp-programming-language] Since the release of C# 2.0 in November 2005, the C# and Java languages have evolved on increasingly divergent trajectories, becoming two quite different languages.
[src:gtk-sharp/c-sharp-programming-language] One of the first major departures came with the addition of generics to both languages, with vastly different implementations.
[src:gtk-sharp/c-sharp-programming-language] C# uses reification to provide "first-class" generic objects that can be used like any other class, with code generation performed at class-load time.
[src:gtk-sharp/c-sharp-programming-language] C# has also added several major features to accommodate functional-style programming, culminating in the LINQ extensions released with C# 3.0 and its supporting framework of lambda expressions, extension methods, and anonymous types.
[src:gtk-sharp/c-sharp-programming-language] These features enable C# programmers to use functional programming techniques, such as closures, when it is advantageous to their application.
[src:gtk-sharp/c-sharp-programming-language] C# used to have a mascot called Andy (named after Anders Hejlsberg).
[src:gtk-sharp/c-sharp-programming-language] C# was originally submitted to the ISO/IEC JTC 1 subcommittee SC 22 for review, under ISO/IEC 23270:2003, was withdrawn and was then approved under ISO/IEC 23270:2006.
[src:gtk-sharp/c-sharp-programming-language] The 23270:2006 is withdrawn under 23270:2018 and approved with this version.
[src:gtk-sharp/c-sharp-programming-language] Microsoft first used the name C# in 1988 for a variant of the C language designed for incremental compilation.
[src:gtk-sharp/c-sharp-programming-language] That project was not completed, and the name was later reused.
[src:gtk-sharp/c-sharp-programming-language] The name "C sharp" was inspired by the musical notation whereby a sharp symbol indicates that the written note should be made a semitone higher in pitch.
[src:gtk-sharp/c-sharp-programming-language] This is similar to the language name of C++, where "++" indicates that a variable should be incremented by 1 after being evaluated.
[src:gtk-sharp/c-sharp-programming-language] The sharp symbol also resembles a ligature of four "+" symbols (in a two-by-two grid), further implying that the language is an increment of C++.
[src:gtk-sharp/c-sharp-programming-language] Due to technical limits of display (standard fonts, browsers, etc.), and most keyboard layouts lacking a sharp symbol (U+266F ♯ MUSIC SHARP SIGN (&sharp;)), the number sign (U+0023 # NUMBER SIGN (&num;)) was chosen to approximate the sharp symbol in the written name of the programming language.
[src:gtk-sharp/c-sharp-programming-language] This convention is reflected in the ECMA-334 C# Language Specification.
[src:gtk-sharp/c-sharp-programming-language] The "sharp" suffix has been used by a number of other Microsoft .NET compatible/compliant languages that are variants of existing languages, including J# (a .NET language also designed by Microsoft that is derived from Java 1.1), A# (from Ada), and the functional programming language F#.
[src:gtk-sharp/c-sharp-programming-language] The original implementation of Eiffel for .NET was called Eiffel#, a name retired since the full Eiffel language is now supported.
[src:gtk-sharp/c-sharp-programming-language] The suffix has also been used for libraries, such as Gtk# (a .NET wrapper for GTK and other GNOME libraries) and Cocoa# (a wrapper for Cocoa).
[src:gtk-sharp/c-sharp-programming-language] Development of the text for standards (beginning with C# 6) is done on GitHub.
[src:gtk-sharp/c-sharp-programming-language] C# 7 was submitted to Ecma and approved in December 2023.
[src:gtk-sharp/c-sharp-programming-language] As of January 2024, the standard for C# 8 is currently under development, referencing the approved language proposals.
[src:gtk-sharp/c-sharp-programming-language] By design, C# is the programming language that most directly reflects the underlying Common Language Infrastructure (CLI).
[src:gtk-sharp/c-sharp-programming-language] Most of its intrinsic types correspond to value-types implemented by the CLI framework.
[src:gtk-sharp/c-sharp-programming-language] However, the language specification does not state the code generation requirements of the compiler: that is, it does not state that a C# compiler must target a Common Language Runtime (CLR), or generate Common Intermediate Language (CIL), or generate any other specific format.
[src:gtk-sharp/c-sharp-programming-language] Some C# compilers can also generate machine code like traditional compilers of Objective-C, C, C++, Assembly and Fortran.
[src:gtk-sharp/c-sharp-programming-language] C# supports strongly, implicitly typed variable declarations with the keyword `var`, and implicitly typed arrays with the keyword `new[]` followed by a collection initializer.
[src:gtk-sharp/c-sharp-programming-language] Due to their special handling of the equality operator and their immutability, strings will nevertheless behave as if they were values, for all practical purposes.
[src:gtk-sharp/c-sharp-programming-language] The programmer can even use them as case labels.
[src:gtk-sharp/c-sharp-programming-language] Where necessary, value types will be boxed automatically.
[src:gtk-sharp/c-sharp-programming-language] C# supports a strict Boolean data type, `bool`.
[src:gtk-sharp/c-sharp-programming-language] Statements that take conditions, such as `while` and `if`, require an expression of a type that evaluates to the `true` boolean value.
[src:gtk-sharp/c-sharp-programming-language] While C++ also has a Boolean type, it can be freely converted to and from integers, and expressions such as `if (a)` require only that `a` is convertible to bool, allowing `a` to be an int, or a pointer.
[src:gtk-sharp/c-sharp-programming-language] C# disallows this "integer meaning true or false" approach, on the grounds that forcing programmers to use expressions that return exactly `bool` can prevent certain types of programming mistakes such as `if (a = b)` (use of assignment `=` instead of equality `==`).
[src:gtk-sharp/c-sharp-programming-language] The only implicit conversions by default are those that are considered safe, such as widening of integers.
[src:gtk-sharp/c-sharp-programming-language] This is enforced at compile-time, during Just-in-time compilation, and, in some cases, at runtime.
[src:gtk-sharp/c-sharp-programming-language] No implicit conversions occur between Booleans and integers, nor between enumeration members and integers (except for literal 0, which can be implicitly converted to any enumerated type).
[src:gtk-sharp/c-sharp-programming-language] Any user-defined conversion must be explicitly marked as explicit or implicit, unlike C++ copy constructors and conversion operators, which are both implicit by default.
[src:gtk-sharp/c-sharp-programming-language] C# has explicit support for covariance and contravariance in generic types, unlike C++ which has some degree of support for contravariance simply through the semantics of return types on virtual methods.
[src:gtk-sharp/c-sharp-programming-language] Enumeration members are placed in their own scope.
[src:gtk-sharp/c-sharp-programming-language] The C# language does not allow for global variables or functions.
[src:gtk-sharp/c-sharp-programming-language] All methods and members must be declared within classes.
[src:gtk-sharp/c-sharp-programming-language] Static members of public classes can substitute for global variables and functions.
[src:gtk-sharp/c-sharp-programming-language] Local variables cannot shadow variables of the enclosing block, unlike C and C++, but may shadow type-level names.
[src:gtk-sharp/c-sharp-programming-language] A *method* in C# is a member of a class that can be invoked as a function, rather than the mere value-holding capability of a *field*, i.e., class or instance variable.
[src:gtk-sharp/c-sharp-programming-language] Different from most other languages, call-by-reference parameters have to be marked both at the function definition and at the calling site, and the programmer can choose between `ref` and `out`, the latter allowing handing over an uninitialized variable which will have a definite value on return.
[src:gtk-sharp/c-sharp-programming-language] Additionally, the programmer can specify a variable-sized argument list by applying the `params` keyword to the last parameter.
[src:gtk-sharp/c-sharp-programming-language] Certain specific kinds of methods, such as those that simply get or set a field's value by returning or assigning it, do not require an explicitly stated full signature, but in the general case, the definition of a class includes the full signature declaration of its methods.
[src:gtk-sharp/c-sharp-programming-language] Like C++, and unlike Java, C# programmers must use the scope modifier keyword `virtual` to allow methods to be overridden by subclasses.
[src:gtk-sharp/c-sharp-programming-language] Unlike C++, the programmer must explicitly specify the keyword `override` when doing so.
[src:gtk-sharp/c-sharp-programming-language] This is supposed to avoid confusion between overriding and newly overloading a function, i.e., hiding the former implementation.
[src:gtk-sharp/c-sharp-programming-language] To do the latter, the programmer has to specify the `new` keyword.
[src:gtk-sharp/c-sharp-programming-language] The keyword `sealed` can be used to disallow further overrides for individual methods or whole classes.
[src:gtk-sharp/c-sharp-programming-language] The type `dynamic` allows for run-time method binding, allowing for JavaScript-like method calls and run-time object composition.
[src:gtk-sharp/c-sharp-programming-language] C# has support for strongly-typed function pointers via the keyword `delegate`.
[src:gtk-sharp/c-sharp-programming-language] Like the Qt framework's pseudo-C++ *signal* and *slot*, C# has semantics specifically surrounding publish-subscribe style events, though C# uses delegates to do so.
[src:gtk-sharp/c-sharp-programming-language] Unlike fields, `event` variables can be part of an interface, because they technically consist of two default functions to add and remove to-be-called delegates.
[src:gtk-sharp/c-sharp-programming-language] C# offers Java-like `synchronized` method calls, via the attribute `[MethodImpl(MethodImplOptions.Synchronized)]`, and has support for mutually-exclusive locks via the keyword `lock`.
[src:gtk-sharp/c-sharp-programming-language] The properties can be simple accessor functions with a backing field, or implement arbitrary getter and setter functions.
[src:gtk-sharp/c-sharp-programming-language] A property is read-only if there's no setter.
[src:gtk-sharp/c-sharp-programming-language] Like with fields, there can be class and instance properties.
[src:gtk-sharp/c-sharp-programming-language] The underlying methods can be `virtual` or `abstract` like any other method.
[src:gtk-sharp/c-sharp-programming-language] Since C# 3.0 the syntactic sugar of auto-implemented properties is available, where the accessor (getter) and mutator (setter) encapsulate operations on a single field of a class.
[src:gtk-sharp/c-sharp-programming-language] A C# `namespace` provides the same level of code isolation as a Java `package` or a C++ `namespace`, with rules and features very similar to a `package`.
[src:gtk-sharp/c-sharp-programming-language] Namespaces can be imported with the "using" syntax.
[src:gtk-sharp/c-sharp-programming-language] In C#, memory address pointers can only be used within blocks specifically marked as *unsafe*, and programs with unsafe code need appropriate permissions to run.
[src:gtk-sharp/c-sharp-programming-language] Most object access is done through safe object references, which always either point to a "live" object or have the well-defined null value; it is impossible to obtain a reference to a "dead" object (one that has been garbage collected), or to an arbitrary block of memory.
[src:gtk-sharp/c-sharp-programming-language] An unsafe pointer can point to an instance of an unmanaged value type that does not contain any references to objects subject to garbage collections such as class instances, arrays or strings.
[src:gtk-sharp/c-sharp-programming-language] Code that is not marked as unsafe can still store and manipulate pointers through the `System.IntPtr` type, but it cannot dereference them.
[src:gtk-sharp/c-sharp-programming-language] Managed memory cannot be explicitly freed; instead, it is automatically garbage collected.
[src:gtk-sharp/c-sharp-programming-language] Garbage collection addresses the problem of memory leaks by freeing the programmer of responsibility for releasing memory that is no longer needed in most cases.
[src:gtk-sharp/c-sharp-programming-language] Code that retains references to objects longer than is required can still experience higher memory usage than necessary, however once the final reference to an object is released the memory is available for garbage collection.
[src:gtk-sharp/c-sharp-programming-language] A range of standard exceptions are available to programmers.
[src:gtk-sharp/c-sharp-programming-language] Methods in standard libraries regularly throw system exceptions in some circumstances and the range of exceptions thrown is normally documented.
[src:gtk-sharp/c-sharp-programming-language] Custom exception classes can be defined for classes allowing handling to be put in place for particular circumstances as needed.
[src:gtk-sharp/c-sharp-programming-language] This is usually called a "try-catch" code block, because of the "try" and "catch" functions being used and accessible on all C# versions.
[src:gtk-sharp/c-sharp-programming-language] If inspecting the error details is not required, the `(Exception ex)` parameter can be omitted as well.
[src:gtk-sharp/c-sharp-programming-language] Also, there can be several "catch" parts handling different kinds of exceptions.
[src:gtk-sharp/c-sharp-programming-language] Checked exceptions are not present in C# (in contrast to Java).
[src:gtk-sharp/c-sharp-programming-language] This has been a conscious decision based on the issues of scalability and version management.
[src:gtk-sharp/c-sharp-programming-language] Unlike C++, C# does not support multiple inheritance, although a class can implement any number of "interfaces" (fully abstract classes).
[src:gtk-sharp/c-sharp-programming-language] This was a design decision by the language's lead architect to avoid complications and to simplify architectural requirements throughout CLI.
[src:gtk-sharp/c-sharp-programming-language] When implementing multiple interfaces that contain a method with the same name and taking parameters of the same types in the same order, i.e., the same signature, similar to Java, C# allows both a single method to cover all interfaces and, if necessary, specific methods for each interface.
[src:gtk-sharp/c-sharp-programming-language] C# also offers function overloading (a.k.a. ad-hoc-polymorphism), i.e., methods with the same name, but distinguishable signatures.
[src:gtk-sharp/c-sharp-programming-language] Unlike Java, C# additionally supports operator overloading.
[src:gtk-sharp/c-sharp-programming-language] Since version 2.0, C# offers parametric polymorphism, i.e., classes with arbitrary or constrained type parameters, e.g., `List<T>`, a variable-sized array which only can contain elements of type `T`.
[src:gtk-sharp/c-sharp-programming-language] There are certain kinds of constraints the programmer can specify for the type parameters: Has to be type X (or one derived from it), has to implement a certain interface, has to be a reference type, has to be a value type, has to implement a public parameterless constructor.
[src:gtk-sharp/c-sharp-programming-language] Most of them can be combined, and any number of interfaces can be specified.
[src:gtk-sharp/c-sharp-programming-language] C# has the ability to utilize LINQ through the .NET Framework.
[src:gtk-sharp/c-sharp-programming-language] A developer can query a variety of data sources, provided the `IEnumerable<T>` interface is implemented on the object.
[src:gtk-sharp/c-sharp-programming-language] This includes XML documents, an ADO.NET dataset, and SQL databases.
[src:gtk-sharp/c-sharp-programming-language] Using LINQ in C# brings advantages like IntelliSense support, strong filtering capabilities, type safety with compile error checking ability, and consistency for querying data over a variety of sources.
[src:gtk-sharp/c-sharp-programming-language] There are several different language structures that can be utilized with C# and LINQ and they are query expressions, lambda expressions, anonymous types, implicitly typed variables, extension methods, and object initializers.
[src:gtk-sharp/c-sharp-programming-language] LINQ has two syntaxes: query syntax and method syntax.
[src:gtk-sharp/c-sharp-programming-language] However, the compiler always converts the query syntax to method syntax at compile time.
[src:gtk-sharp/c-sharp-programming-language] This unified type system is called Common Type System (CTS).
[src:gtk-sharp/c-sharp-programming-language] A unified type system implies that all types, including primitives such as integers, are subclasses of the `System.Object` class.
[src:gtk-sharp/c-sharp-programming-language] For example, every type inherits a `ToString()` method.
[src:gtk-sharp/c-sharp-programming-language] Instances of value types neither have referential identity nor referential comparison semantics.
[src:gtk-sharp/c-sharp-programming-language] Equality and inequality comparisons for value types compare the actual data values within the instances, unless the corresponding operators are overloaded.
[src:gtk-sharp/c-sharp-programming-language] Value types are derived from `System.ValueType`, always have a default value, and can always be created and copied.
[src:gtk-sharp/c-sharp-programming-language] Other examples are `enum` (enumerations) and `struct` (user defined structures).
[src:gtk-sharp/c-sharp-programming-language] In contrast, reference types have the notion of referential identity, meaning that each instance of a reference type is inherently distinct from every other instance, even if the data within both instances is the same.
[src:gtk-sharp/c-sharp-programming-language] This is reflected in default equality and inequality comparisons for reference types, which test for referential rather than structural equality, unless the corresponding operators are overloaded (such as the case for `System.String`).
[src:gtk-sharp/c-sharp-programming-language] Some operations are not always possible, such as creating an instance of a reference type, copying an existing instance, or performing a value comparison on two existing instances.
[src:gtk-sharp/c-sharp-programming-language] Nevertheless, specific reference types can provide such services by exposing a public constructor or implementing a corresponding interface (such as `ICloneable` or `IComparable`).
[src:gtk-sharp/c-sharp-programming-language] Examples of reference types are `object` (the ultimate base class for all other C# classes), `System.String` (a string of Unicode characters), and `System.Array` (a base class for all C# arrays).
[src:gtk-sharp/c-sharp-programming-language] Both type categories are extensible with user-defined types.
[src:gtk-sharp/c-sharp-programming-language] The C# specification details a minimum set of types and class libraries that the compiler expects to have available.
[src:gtk-sharp/c-sharp-programming-language] In practice, C# is most often used with some implementation of the Common Language Infrastructure (CLI), which is standardized as ECMA-335 *Common Language Infrastructure (CLI)*.
[src:gtk-sharp/c-sharp-programming-language] In addition to the standard CLI specifications, there are many commercial and community class libraries that build on top of the .NET framework libraries to provide additional functionality.
[src:gtk-sharp/c-sharp-programming-language] C# can make calls to any library included in the List of .NET libraries and frameworks.
[src:gtk-sharp/c-sharp-programming-language] The line above imports all types in the `System` namespace.
[src:gtk-sharp/c-sharp-programming-language] For example, the `Console` class used later in the source code is defined in the `System` namespace, meaning it can be used without supplying the full name of the type (which includes the namespace).
[src:gtk-sharp/c-sharp-programming-language] This line is a comment; it describes and documents the code for the programmer(s).
[src:gtk-sharp/c-sharp-programming-language] Above is a class definition for the `Program` class.
[src:gtk-sharp/c-sharp-programming-language] Everything that follows between the pair of braces describes that class.
[src:gtk-sharp/c-sharp-programming-language] The curly brackets demarcate the boundaries of a code block.
[src:gtk-sharp/c-sharp-programming-language] In this first instance, they are marking the start and end of the `Program` class.
[src:gtk-sharp/c-sharp-programming-language] This declares the class member method where the program begins execution.
[src:gtk-sharp/c-sharp-programming-language] The .NET runtime calls the `Main` method.
[src:gtk-sharp/c-sharp-programming-language] Unlike in Java, the `Main` method does not need the `public` keyword, which tells the compiler that the method can be called from anywhere by any class.
[src:gtk-sharp/c-sharp-programming-language] Writing `static void Main(string[] args)` is equivalent to writing `private static void Main(string[] args)`.
[src:gtk-sharp/c-sharp-programming-language] The static keyword makes the method accessible without an instance of `Program`.
[src:gtk-sharp/c-sharp-programming-language] Each console application's `Main` entry point must be declared `static` otherwise the program would require an instance of `Program`, but any instance would require a program.
[src:gtk-sharp/c-sharp-programming-language] To avoid that irresolvable circular dependency, C# compilers processing console applications (like that above) report an error if there is no `static Main` method.
[src:gtk-sharp/c-sharp-programming-language] The `void` keyword declares that `Main` has no return value.
[src:gtk-sharp/c-sharp-programming-language] `Console` is a static class in the `System` namespace.
[src:gtk-sharp/c-sharp-programming-language] It provides an interface to the standard input/output, and error streams for console applications.
[src:gtk-sharp/c-sharp-programming-language] The program calls the `Console` method `WriteLine`, which displays on the console a line with the argument, the string `"Hello, World!"`.
[src:gtk-sharp/c-sharp-programming-language] With .NET 2.0 and C# 2.0, the community got more flexible collections than those in .NET 1.x.
[src:gtk-sharp/c-sharp-programming-language] In the absence of generics, developers had to use collections such as ArrayList to store elements as objects of unspecified kind, which incurred performance overhead when boxing/unboxing/type-checking the contained items.
[src:gtk-sharp/c-sharp-programming-language] Generics introduced a massive new feature in .NET that allowed developers to create type-safe data structures.
[src:gtk-sharp/c-sharp-programming-language] This shift is particularly important in the context of converting legacy systems, where updating to generics can significantly enhance performance and maintainability by replacing outdated data structures with more efficient, type-safe alternatives.
[src:gtk-sharp/c-sharp-programming-language] In August 2001, Microsoft, Hewlett-Packard and Intel co-sponsored the submission of specifications for C# as well as the Common Language Infrastructure (CLI) to the standards organization Ecma International.
[src:gtk-sharp/c-sharp-programming-language] In December 2001, ECMA released ECMA-334 *C# Language Specification*.
[src:gtk-sharp/c-sharp-programming-language] C# became an ISO/IEC standard in 2003 (ISO/IEC 23270:2003 - *Information technology — Programming languages — C#*).
[src:gtk-sharp/c-sharp-programming-language] ECMA had previously adopted equivalent specifications as the 2nd edition of C#, in December 2002.
[src:gtk-sharp/c-sharp-programming-language] In June 2005, ECMA approved edition 3 of the C# specification, and updated ECMA-334.
[src:gtk-sharp/c-sharp-programming-language] Additions included partial classes, anonymous methods, nullable types, and generics (somewhat similar to C++ templates).
[src:gtk-sharp/c-sharp-programming-language] In July 2005, ECMA submitted to ISO/IEC JTC 1/SC 22, via the latter's Fast-Track process, the standards and related TRs.
[src:gtk-sharp/c-sharp-programming-language] The C# language definition and the CLI are standardized under ISO/IEC and Ecma standards that provide reasonable and non-discriminatory licensing protection from patent claims.
[src:gtk-sharp/c-sharp-programming-language] Microsoft initially agreed not to sue open-source developers for violating patents in non-profit projects for the part of the framework that is covered by the Open Specification Promise.
[src:gtk-sharp/c-sharp-programming-language] Microsoft has also agreed not to enforce patents relating to Novell products against Novell's paying customers with the exception of a list of products that do not explicitly mention C#, .NET or Novell's implementation of .NET (The Mono Project).
[src:gtk-sharp/c-sharp-programming-language] However, Novell maintained that Mono does not infringe any Microsoft patents.
[src:gtk-sharp/c-sharp-programming-language] Microsoft also made a specific agreement not to enforce patent rights related to the Moonlight browser plugin, which depends on Mono, provided it is obtained through Novell.
[src:gtk-sharp/c-sharp-programming-language] A decade later, Microsoft began developing free, open-source, and cross-platform tooling for C#, namely Visual Studio Code, .NET Core, and Roslyn.
[src:gtk-sharp/c-sharp-programming-language] Mono joined Microsoft as a project of Xamarin, a Microsoft subsidiary.
[src:gtk-sharp/c-sharp-programming-language] Microsoft has developed open-source reference C# compilers and tools.
[src:gtk-sharp/c-sharp-programming-language] The first compiler, Roslyn, compiles into intermediate language (IL), and the second one, RyuJIT, is a JIT (just-in-time) compiler, which is dynamic and does on-the-fly optimization and compiles the IL into native code for the front-end of the CPU.
[src:gtk-sharp/c-sharp-programming-language] RyuJIT is open source and written in C++.
[src:gtk-sharp/c-sharp-programming-language] Roslyn is entirely written in managed code (C#), has been opened up and functionality surfaced as APIs.
[src:gtk-sharp/c-sharp-programming-language] It is thus enabling developers to create refactoring and diagnostics tools.
[src:gtk-sharp/c-sharp-programming-language] Two branches of official implementation are .NET Framework (closed-source, Windows-only) and .NET Core (open-source, cross-platform); they eventually converged into one open-source implementation: .NET 5.0.
[src:gtk-sharp/c-sharp-programming-language] At .NET Framework 4.6, a new JIT compiler replaced the former.
[src:gtk-sharp/c-sharp-programming-language] The Unity game engine uses C# as its primary scripting language.
[src:gtk-sharp/c-sharp-programming-language] The Godot game engine has implemented an optional C# module due to a donation of $24,000 from Microsoft.
[src:gtk-sharp/gobject] The **GLib Object System**, or **GObject**, is a free software library providing a portable object system and transparent cross-language interoperability.
[src:gtk-sharp/gobject] GObject is designed for use both directly in C programs to provide object-oriented C-based APIs and through bindings to other languages to provide transparent cross-language interoperability, e.g.
[src:gtk-sharp/gobject] Depending only on GLib and libc, GObject is a cornerstone of GNOME and is used throughout GTK, Pango, ATK, and most higher-level GNOME libraries like GStreamer and applications.
[src:gtk-sharp/gobject] Prior to GTK+ 2.0, code similar to GObject was part of the GTK codebase.
[src:gtk-sharp/gobject] At the release of GTK+ 2.0, the object system was extracted into a separate library due to its general utility.
[src:gtk-sharp/gobject] In the process, most non-GUI-specific parts of the `GtkObject` class were moved up into `GObject`, the new common baseclass.
[src:gtk-sharp/gobject] Having existed as a separate library since March 11, 2002 (the release date of GTK+ 2.0), the GObject library is now used by many non-GUI programs such as command-line and server applications.
[src:gtk-sharp/gobject] Though GObject has its own separate set of documentation and is usually compiled into its own shared library file, the source code for GObject resides in the GLib source tree and is distributed along with GLib.
[src:gtk-sharp/gobject] For this reason, GObject uses the GLib version numbers and is typically packaged together with GLib (for example, Debian puts GObject in its `libglib2.0` package family).
[src:gtk-sharp/gobject] At the most basic level of the GObject framework lies a generic and dynamic type system called GType.
[src:gtk-sharp/gobject] The GType system holds a runtime description of all objects allowing glue code to facilitate multiple language bindings.
[src:gtk-sharp/gobject] The type system can handle any singly inherited class structure, in addition to *non-classed* types such as opaque pointers, strings, and variously sized integers and floating point numbers.
[src:gtk-sharp/gobject] The type system knows how to copy, assign, and destroy values belonging to any of the registered types.
[src:gtk-sharp/gobject] This is trivial for types like integers, but many complex objects are reference-counted, while some are complex but not reference-counted.
[src:gtk-sharp/gobject] When the type system "copies" a reference-counted object, it will typically just increase its reference count, whereas when copying a complex, non-reference-counted object (such as a string), it will typically create an actual copy by allocating memory.
[src:gtk-sharp/gobject] This basic functionality is used for implementing `GValue`, a type of generic container that can hold values of any type known by the type system.
[src:gtk-sharp/gobject] Such containers are particularly useful when interacting with dynamically typed language environments in which all native values reside in such type-tagged containers.
[src:gtk-sharp/gobject] Types that do not have any associated classes are called *non-classed*.
[src:gtk-sharp/gobject] These types, together with all types that correspond to some form of root class, are known as *fundamental types*: the types from which all other types are derived.
[src:gtk-sharp/gobject] These make up a relatively closed set, but although the average user is not expected to create their own fundamental types, the possibility does exist and has been exploited to create custom class hierarchies — i.e., class hierarchies not based on the `GObject` class.
[src:gtk-sharp/gobject] Types that can be instantiated automatically by the type system are called *instantiable*.
[src:gtk-sharp/gobject] An important characteristic of these types is that the first bytes of any instance always contain a pointer to the *class structure* (a form of virtual table) associated to the type of the instance.
[src:gtk-sharp/gobject] For this reason, any instantiable type must be classed.
[src:gtk-sharp/gobject] Contrapositively, any non-classed type (such as *integer* or *string*) must be non-instantiable.
[src:gtk-sharp/gobject] On the other hand, most classed types are instantiable, but some, such as interface types, are not.
[src:gtk-sharp/gobject] should be registered with the type system.
[src:gtk-sharp/gobject] Some data structures that are too simple to be made full-fledged class types (with all the overhead incurred) may still need to be registered with the type system.
[src:gtk-sharp/gobject] to represent this structure, and provide functions for copying and freeing.
[src:gtk-sharp/gobject] GObject ships with a handful of boxed types wrapping simple GLib data types.
[src:gtk-sharp/gobject] Another use for boxed types is as a way to wrap foreign objects in a tagged container that the type system can identify and will know how to copy and free.
[src:gtk-sharp/gobject] Sometimes, for objects that need to be neither copied or reference-counted nor freed, even a boxed type would be overkill.
[src:gtk-sharp/gobject] ), it is often a good idea to create a derived pointer type, documenting the fact that the pointers should reference a particular kind of object, even though nothing else is said about it.
[src:gtk-sharp/gobject] The GObject messaging system consists of two complementary parts: *closures* and *signals*.
[src:gtk-sharp/gobject] Support exists for closures written in C and C++, as well as arbitrary languages (when bindings are provided).
[src:gtk-sharp/gobject] This allows code written in (for example) Python and Java to be invoked via a GObject closure.
[src:gtk-sharp/gobject] Signals are the primary mechanism by which closures are invoked.
[src:gtk-sharp/gobject] Objects register signal listeners with the type system, specifying a mapping between a given signal and a given closure.
[src:gtk-sharp/gobject] Upon emission of a registered signal, that signal's closure is invoked.
[src:gtk-sharp/gobject] In GTK, all native GUI events (such as mouse motion and keyboard actions) can generate GObject signals for listeners to potentially act upon.
[src:gtk-sharp/gobject] Each GObject class is implemented by at least two structures: the *class structure* and the *instance structure*.
[src:gtk-sharp/gobject] It must begin with the class structure of the superclass.
[src:gtk-sharp/gobject] Class-specific variables can be used to emulate class members.
[src:gtk-sharp/gobject] (this ensures that all instances begin with a pointer to the class structure, since all fundamental instantiable types share this property).
[src:gtk-sharp/gobject] After the data belonging to the superclass, the structure can hold any instance-specific variables, corresponding to C++ member variables.
[src:gtk-sharp/gobject] Defining a class in the GObject framework is complex, requiring large amounts of boilerplate code, such as manual definitions of type casting macros and obscure type registration incantations.
[src:gtk-sharp/gobject] Also, since a C structure cannot have access modifiers like "public", "protected", or "private", workarounds must be used to provide encapsulation.
[src:gtk-sharp/gobject] One approach is to include a pointer to the private data — conventionally called `_priv` — in the instance structure.
[src:gtk-sharp/gobject] The *private structure* can be declared in the public header file, but defined only in the implementation file, with the effect that the private data is opaque to users, but transparent to the implementor.
[src:gtk-sharp/gobject] If the private structure is registered with GType, it will be automatically allocated by the object system.
[src:gtk-sharp/gobject] Indeed, it is not even necessary to include the `_priv` pointer, if one is willing to use the incantation `G_TYPE_INSTANCE_GET_PRIVATE` every time the private data is needed.
[src:gtk-sharp/gobject] To address some of these complexities, several higher-level languages exist that source-to-source compiles to GObject in C.
[src:gtk-sharp/gobject] The Vala programming language uses a C#-style syntax and is pre-processed into vanilla C code.
[src:gtk-sharp/gobject] The GObject Builder, or GOB2, offers a template syntax reminiscent of Java.
[src:gtk-sharp/gobject] The combination of C and GObject is used in many successful free software projects, such as the GNOME desktop, the GTK toolkit and the GIMP image manipulation program.
[src:gtk-sharp/gobject] Though many GObject applications are written entirely in C, the GObject system maps well into the native object systems of many other languages, like C++, Java, Ruby, Python, Common Lisp, and .NET/Mono.
[src:gtk-sharp/gobject] As a result, it is usually relatively painless to create language bindings for well-written libraries that use the GObject framework.
[src:gtk-sharp/gobject] For example, many Python programs use libraries written in C that use the GObject framework by using the PyGObject language binding.
[src:gtk-sharp/gobject] (A few of them are listed at Category:Software that uses PyGObject).
[src:gtk-sharp/gobject] Writing GObject code in C in the first place, however, is relatively verbose.
[src:gtk-sharp/gobject] The library takes a good deal of time to learn, and programmers with experience in high-level object-oriented languages often find it somewhat tedious to work with GObject in C.
[src:gtk-sharp/gobject] For example, creating a subclass (even just a subclass of `GObject`) can require writing and/or copying large amounts of boilerplate code.
[src:gtk-sharp/gobject] However, using Vala, a language that is designed primarily to work with GObject and which converts to C, is likely to make working with GObject or writing GObject based libraries nicer.
[src:gtk-sharp/gobject] Although they are not really first-class objects (there are no actual metatypes in GType), metaobjects like classes and interfaces are created by GObject applications at runtime, and provide good support for introspection.
[src:gtk-sharp/gobject] Since GObject provides a mostly complete object system for C, it can be seen as an alternative to C-derived languages such as C++ and Objective-C, though both also offer many other features beyond just their respective object systems.
[src:gtk-sharp/gobject] An easily observed difference between C++ and GObject is that GObject (like Java) does not support multiple inheritance.
[src:gtk-sharp/gobject] This tends to work against including GObject in software where resilience in the face of limited memory is important, or where very many or very large objects are commonly handled.
[src:gtk-sharp/gobject] The g_try_new() can be used when a memory allocation is more likely to fail (for a large object for example), but this cannot grant that the allocation will not fail elsewhere in the code.
[src:gtk-sharp/gobject] Another important difference is that while C++ and Objective-C are separate languages, GObject is strictly a library and as such does not introduce any new syntax or compiler intelligence.
[src:gtk-sharp/gobject] For example, when writing GObject-based C code, it is frequently necessary to perform explicit upcasting.
[src:gtk-sharp/gobject] Hence, "C with GObject", also called "glib-flavored C", considered as a language separate from plain C, is a strict superset of plain C — like Objective C, but unlike C++.
[src:gtk-sharp/gobject] On platforms where there is no standard ABI that works across all C++ compilers (which is not usually the case, since either the Itanium ABI or the Microsoft ABI are usually followed), a library compiled with one C++ compiler is not always able to call a library compiled with a different one.
[src:gtk-sharp/gobject] If such compatibility is required, the C++ methods must be exported as plain C functions, partly defeating the purpose of the C++ object system.
[src:gtk-sharp/gobject] The problem occurs in part because different C++ compilers use different kinds of name mangling to ensure the uniqueness of all exported symbols.
[src:gtk-sharp/gobject] Hence, despite being object-oriented, a GObject-based library written in C will always use the same external symbol names regardless of which compiler is used.
[src:gtk-sharp/gobject] Perhaps the most profound difference is GObject's emphasis on signals (called events in other languages).
[src:gtk-sharp/gobject] This emphasis derives from the fact that GObject was specifically designed to meet the needs of a GUI toolkit.
[src:gtk-sharp/gobject] Whilst there are signal libraries for most object-oriented languages out there, in the case of GObject it is built into the object system.
[src:gtk-sharp/gobject] Because of this, a typical GObject application will tend to use signals to a much larger extent than a non-GObject application would, making GObject components much more encapsulated and reusable than the ones using plain C++ or Java.
[src:gtk-sharp/gobject] If using glibmm/gtkmm, the official C++ wrappers to Glib/GTK respectively, the sibling project libsigc++ allows easy use of underlying GObject signals using standard C++.
[src:gtk-sharp/gobject] Of course, other implementations of signals are available on almost all platforms, although sometimes an extra library is needed, such as Boost.Signals2 for C++.
[src:gtk-sharp/gtk] The GTK team releases new versions on a regular basis.
[src:gtk-sharp/gtk] GTK 4 and GTK 3 are actively maintained, while GTK 2 is no longer supported.
[src:gtk-sharp/gtk] GTK 1 is independently maintained by the CinePaint project.
[src:gtk-sharp/gtk] The GTK library contains a set of graphical control elements (widgets); version 3.22.16 contains 186 active and 36 deprecated widgets.
[src:gtk-sharp/gtk] GTK is an object-oriented widget toolkit written in the programming language C; it uses GObject (that is, the GLib object system) for object orientation.
[src:gtk-sharp/gtk] While GTK is mainly used with windowing systems based on Wayland (and prior to that on Wayland's predecessor X11), it works on other platforms, including Microsoft Windows (interfaced with the Windows API), and macOS (interfaced with Quartz).
[src:gtk-sharp/gtk] There is also an HTML5 back-end named *Broadway*, although this was deprecated in 2025 with the X11 backend to indicate both would be removed in GTK version 5.
[src:gtk-sharp/gtk] GTK uses Vulkan or GL to draw most graphical elements.
[src:gtk-sharp/gtk] GTK can be configured to change the look of the widgets drawn with its CSS engine.
[src:gtk-sharp/gtk] CSS can be used both at the system/user level, for all applications, and set by the application.
[src:gtk-sharp/gtk] GDK acts as a wrapper around the low-level functions provided by the underlying windowing and graphics systems.
[src:gtk-sharp/gtk] GSK is the rendering and scene graph API for GTK.
[src:gtk-sharp/gtk] GSK lies between the graphical control elements (widgets) and the rendering.
[src:gtk-sharp/gtk] GSK was finally merged into GTK version 3.90 released March 2017.
[src:gtk-sharp/gtk] GtkBuilder allows user interfaces to be designed without writing code.
[src:gtk-sharp/gtk] The interface is described in an Extensible Markup Language (XML) file which is written by hand or generated by a GUI designer, which is then loaded at runtime and the objects created automatically.
[src:gtk-sharp/gtk] The description of the user interface is independent from the programming language being used.
[src:gtk-sharp/gtk] Language bindings are available for using GTK from languages other than C, including C++, Genie, JavaScript, Perl, Python, Vala, and others.
[src:gtk-sharp/gtk] GTK supports various backends, which provides different ways to display GTK applications depending on the system and environment.
[src:gtk-sharp/gtk] There are several GUI designers for GTK.
[src:gtk-sharp/gtk] The GTK Inspector is a built-in interactive debugging tool in GTK, allowing developers to inspect and modify UI elements, test CSS changes, and analyze widget structure in real time.
[src:gtk-sharp/gtk] It can be enabled using the `Control + Shift + I` or `Control + Shift + D` shortcuts, or by setting the `GTK_DEBUG=interactive` environment variable.
[src:gtk-sharp/gtk] It was introduced with GTK version 3.14.
[src:gtk-sharp/gtk] GTK is mainly developed by The GNOME Project, which also develops the GNOME Development Platform and the GNOME Desktop Environment.
[src:gtk-sharp/gtk] GNOME developers and users gather at an annual *GNOME Users And Developers European Conference* GUADEC meeting to discuss GNOME's current state and future direction.
[src:gtk-sharp/gtk] GNOME incorporates standards and programs from freedesktop.org to better interoperate with other desktops.
[src:gtk-sharp/gtk] Many GNOME applications have been ported to GTK 4, which was released in December 2020, however some still use GTK+ 3 (GIMP being a major one).
[src:gtk-sharp/gtk] The master branch of GTK utilizes Meson for its build automation.
[src:gtk-sharp/gtk] GTK (and GNOME, GLib, etc.) formerly utilized the GNU Build System (named Autotools) as the build automation system of choice.
[src:gtk-sharp/gtk] Since August 14, 2017, the Autotools build system files have been dropped.
[src:gtk-sharp/gtk] The most common criticism of GTK is the lack of backward-compatibility in major updates, most notably in the application programming interface (API) and theming.
[src:gtk-sharp/gtk] As a result, application and theme developers often have to rewrite parts of their code to ensure compatibility with newer version of GTK.
[src:gtk-sharp/gtk] The compatibility breaks between minor releases during the GTK 3.x development cycle was explained in 2013 by Benjamin Otte as due to strong pressures to innovate, such as providing the features modern users expect and supporting the increasingly influential Wayland display server protocol.
[src:gtk-sharp/gtk] With the release of GTK 4, the pressure from the need to innovate will have been released and the balance between stability and innovation will tip toward stability.
[src:gtk-sharp/gtk] Similarly, recent changes to theming are specifically intended to improve and stabilise that part of the API, meaning some investment now should be rewarded later.
[src:gtk-sharp/gtk] However, in 2025, GTK 5 is described in the official documentation as "a major new version of GTK that breaks both API and ABI compared to GTK 4.x.", like GTK 3 and 4.
[src:gtk-sharp/gtk] GTK programs can be run on desktop environments based on X11 and Wayland, or others including ones not made with GTK, provided the needed libraries are installed; this includes macOS if X11.app is installed.
[src:gtk-sharp/gtk] GTK can be also run on Microsoft Windows.
[src:gtk-sharp/gtk] It is used by some popular cross-platform applications like Pidgin and GIMP. wxWidgets, a cross-platform GUI toolkit, uses GTK on Linux by default.
[src:gtk-sharp/gtk] Other ports include DirectFB (for example used by the Debian installer).
[src:gtk-sharp/gtk] Several desktop environments utilize GTK as the widget toolkit.
[src:gtk-sharp/gtk] For syntax highlighting there is GtkSourceView, "source code editing widget".
[src:gtk-sharp/gtk] GtkSourceView is maintained by GNOME separately from GTK as a library: gtksourceview.
[src:gtk-sharp/gtk] GtkSpell is a library separate from GTK.
[src:gtk-sharp/gtk] Enchant is a wrapper for ispell, hunspell, etc., the actual spell checker engine/software.
[src:gtk-sharp/gtk] GtkSpell uses GTK's GtkTextView widget, to highlight misspelled words and offer replacement.
[src:gtk-sharp/gtk] Finally GTK was re-written to be object-oriented and was renamed GTK+.
[src:gtk-sharp/gtk] This was first used in the 0.99 release of GIMP.
[src:gtk-sharp/gtk] GTK was subsequently adopted for maintenance by the GNOME Foundation, which uses it in the GNOME desktop environment.
[src:gtk-sharp/gtk] The GTK 2.0.0 release (2002) series introduced new features which include improved text rendering using Pango, a new theme engine, improved accessibility using the Accessibility Toolkit, transition to Unicode using UTF-8 strings, and a more flexible API.
[src:gtk-sharp/gtk] Starting with version 2.8, released in 2005, GTK 2 depends on the Cairo graphics library for rendering vector graphics.
[src:gtk-sharp/gtk] GTK version 3.0.0 (2011) included revised input device handling, support for themes written with CSS-like syntax, and the ability to receive information about other opened GTK applications.
[src:gtk-sharp/gtk] The '+' was dropped returning to simply 'GTK' in February 2019 during a Hackathon.
[src:gtk-sharp/gtk] Release of the first GTK 4 version was in December 2020.
[src:gtk-sharp/gtk] At the 2018 edition of DevConf.cz, Matthias Clasen gave an overview of the then-current state of GTK 4 development, including a high-level explanation of how rendering and input worked in GTK 3, what changes were being made to GTK 4, and the reasons for those changes.
[src:gtk-sharp/gtk] Examples of things that have become possible with GTK 4 were given as well.
[src:gtk-sharp/gtk] One of the main changes made during the GTK 4 development cycle (i.e.
[src:gtk-sharp/gtk] GTK 3.92, etc.) was the removal of user customization options (like individual keyboard shortcuts that could be set in GTK+ 2), and the delegation of functionality to ancillary objects instead of encoding it into the base classes provided by GTK.
[src:gtk-sharp/language-binding] In programming and software design, a **binding** is an application programming interface (API) that provides glue code specifically made to allow a programming language to use a foreign library or operating system service (one that is not native to that language).
[src:gtk-sharp/language-binding] Binding generally refers to a mapping of one thing to another.
[src:gtk-sharp/language-binding] In the context of software libraries, bindings are wrapper libraries that bridge two programming languages, so that a library written for one language can be used in another language.
[src:gtk-sharp/language-binding] Many software libraries are written in system programming languages such as C or C++.
[src:gtk-sharp/language-binding] To use such libraries from another language, usually of higher-level, such as Java, Common Lisp, Scheme, Python, or Lua, a binding to the library must be created in that language, possibly requiring recompiling the language's code, depending on the amount of modification needed.
[src:gtk-sharp/language-binding] However, most languages offer a foreign function interface, such as Python's and OCaml's `ctypes`, and Embeddable Common Lisp's `cffi` and `uffi`.
[src:gtk-sharp/language-binding] For example, Python bindings are used when an extant C library, written for some purpose, is to be used from Python.
[src:gtk-sharp/language-binding] Another example is `libsvn` which is written in C to provide an API to access the Subversion software repository.
[src:gtk-sharp/language-binding] To access Subversion from within Java code, `libsvnjavahl` can be used, which depends on `libsvn` being installed and acts as a bridge between the language Java and `libsvn`, thus providing an API that invokes functions from `libsvn` to do the work.
[src:gtk-sharp/language-binding] Major motives to create library bindings include software reuse, to reduce reimplementing a library in several languages, and the difficulty of implementing some algorithms efficiently in some high-level languages.
[src:gtk-sharp/mono-software] Miguel de Icaza of Ximian believed that .NET had the potential to increase programmer productivity and began investigating whether a Linux version was feasible.
[src:gtk-sharp/mono-software] Recognizing that their small team could not expect to build and support a full product, they launched the Mono open-source project, on July 19, 2001, at the O'Reilly conference.
[src:gtk-sharp/mono-software] After three years of development, Mono 1.0 was released on June 30, 2004.
[src:gtk-sharp/mono-software] Mono evolved from its initial focus of a developer platform for Linux desktop applications to supporting a wide range of architectures and operating systems - including embedded systems.
[src:gtk-sharp/mono-software] After Novell was acquired by Attachmate in April 2011, Attachmate announced hundreds of layoffs for the Novell workforce, putting in question the future of Mono.
[src:gtk-sharp/mono-software] On May 16, 2011, Miguel de Icaza announced in his blog that Mono would continue to be supported by Xamarin, a company he founded after being laid off from Novell.
[src:gtk-sharp/mono-software] The original Mono team had also moved to the new company.
[src:gtk-sharp/mono-software] Xamarin planned to keep working on Mono and had planned to rewrite the proprietary .NET stacks for iOS and Android from scratch, because Novell still owned MonoTouch and Mono for Android at the time.
[src:gtk-sharp/mono-software] However, in July 2011, Novell, now a subsidiary of Attachmate, and Xamarin, announced that it granted a perpetual license to Xamarin for Mono, MonoTouch and Mono for Android, which officially took stewardship of the project.
[src:gtk-sharp/mono-software] On February 24, 2016, Microsoft announced it had signed a definitive agreement to acquire Xamarin.
[src:gtk-sharp/mono-software] On August 27, 2024, Microsoft transferred ownership of Mono to WineHQ, the developer team of Wine, a Windows compatibility layer.
[src:gtk-sharp/mono-software] Mono's current version is 6.12.0 (as of June 2024).
[src:gtk-sharp/mono-software] This version provides the core API of the .NET Framework and support for Visual Basic.NET and C# 7.0.
[src:gtk-sharp/mono-software] LINQ to Objects, XML, and SQL are part of the distribution.
[src:gtk-sharp/mono-software] Windows Forms 2.0 is also supported, but not actively developed, and as such its support on Mono is incomplete.
[src:gtk-sharp/mono-software] Version 4.0 was the first version that incorporates Microsoft original source code that was released by Microsoft as part of the .NET Core project.
[src:gtk-sharp/mono-software] However, System.Web and WCF are candidates for 'almost immediate' porting from the .NET reference source back to Mono.
[src:gtk-sharp/mono-software] Some missing parts of the .NET Framework are under development in an experimental Mono subproject called *Olive*.
[src:gtk-sharp/mono-software] The Mono project has also created a Visual Basic .NET compiler and a runtime designed for running VB.NET applications.
[src:gtk-sharp/mono-software] It is currently being developed by Rolf Bjarne Kvinge.
[src:gtk-sharp/mono-software] An open-source implementation of Microsoft Silverlight, called Moonlight, has been included since Mono 1.9.
[src:gtk-sharp/mono-software] Moonlight 1.0, which supports the Silverlight 1.0 APIs, was released January 20, 2009.
[src:gtk-sharp/mono-software] Moonlight 2.0 supports Silverlight 2.0 and some features of Silverlight 3.0.
[src:gtk-sharp/mono-software] A preview release of Moonlight 3.0 was announced in February 2010 and contains updates to Silverlight 3 support.
[src:gtk-sharp/mono-software] The Moonlight project was abandoned on May 29, 2012.
[src:gtk-sharp/mono-software] According to Miguel, two factors sealed the fate of the project: Microsoft added "artificial restrictions" that "made it useless for desktop programming", and the technology had not gained enough traction on the Web.
[src:gtk-sharp/mono-software] In addition, Silverlight itself was deprecated by Microsoft by 2012.
[src:gtk-sharp/mono-software] The *core components* include the C# compiler, the virtual machine for the Common Language Infrastructure and the core class libraries.
[src:gtk-sharp/mono-software] These components are based on the Ecma-334 and Ecma-335 standards, allowing Mono to provide a standards compliant, free and open-source CLI virtual machine.
[src:gtk-sharp/mono-software] Microsoft issued a statement that covers both standards under their Community Promise license.
[src:gtk-sharp/mono-software] The *Mono/Linux/GNOME development stack* provide tools for application development while using the existing GNOME and free and open-source libraries.
[src:gtk-sharp/mono-software] These include: Gtk# for graphical user interface (GUI) development, Mozilla libraries for working with the Gecko rendering engine, Unix integration libraries (Mono.Posix), database connectivity libraries, a security stack, and the XML schema language RelaxNG.
[src:gtk-sharp/mono-software] Gtk# allows Mono applications to integrate into the Gnome desktop as native applications.
[src:gtk-sharp/mono-software] The database libraries provide connectivity to the object-relational database db4o, Firebird, Microsoft SQL Server (MSSQL), MySQL, Open Database Connectivity (ODBC), Oracle, PostgreSQL, SQLite, and many others.
[src:gtk-sharp/mono-software] The Mono project tracks developing database components at its website.
[src:gtk-sharp/mono-software] The *Microsoft compatibility stack* provides a pathway for porting Windows .NET applications to Linux.
[src:gtk-sharp/mono-software] This group of components include ADO.NET, ASP.NET, and Windows Forms (and libgdiplus), among others.
[src:gtk-sharp/mono-software] As these components are not covered by Ecma standards, some of them remain subject to patent fears and concerns.
[src:gtk-sharp/mono-software] The Mono runtime contains a code execution engine that translates ECMA CIL byte codes into native code and supports a number of processors: ARM, MIPS (in 32-bit mode only), SPARC, PowerPC, z/Architecture, IA-32, x86-64 and IA-64 for 64-bit modes.
[src:gtk-sharp/mono-software] Starting with Mono 2.6, it is possible to configure Mono to use the LLVM as the code generation engine instead of Mono's own code generation engine.
[src:gtk-sharp/mono-software] This is useful for high performance computing loads and other situations where the execution performance is more important than the startup performance.
[src:gtk-sharp/mono-software] Starting with the Mono 2.7 preview, it is no longer necessary to pick one engine over the other at configuration time.
[src:gtk-sharp/mono-software] The code generation engine can be selected at startup by using the `--llvm` or `--nollvm` command line arguments, and it defaults to the fast-starting Mono code generation engine.
[src:gtk-sharp/mono-software] Starting with Mono 5.18, support for LLVM is a default configuration option.
[src:gtk-sharp/mono-software] Previous versions required a special LLVM fork, but now mono can fall back to its own code generator when it encounters something not handled by LLVM.
[src:gtk-sharp/mono-software] As of Mono 2.8, the Mono runtime ships with two garbage collectors: a generational collector and the *Boehm–Demers–Weiser Conservative Garbage Collector*.
[src:gtk-sharp/mono-software] The Boehm garbage collector could exhibit memory leaks on certain classes of applications, making it unsuitable for some long-running server applications.
[src:gtk-sharp/mono-software] Mono switched to *Simple Generational GC* (SGen-GC) as the default collector in version 3.1.1.
[src:gtk-sharp/mono-software] The SGen garbage collector has many advantages over a traditional conservative scanner.
[src:gtk-sharp/mono-software] It uses generational garbage collection where new objects are allocated from a nursery, during the garbage collection cycle, all objects that survived are migrated to an older generation memory pool.
[src:gtk-sharp/mono-software] The idea is that many objects are transient and can quickly be collected and only a handful of objects are long-term objects that live for the entire life of the application.
[src:gtk-sharp/mono-software] To improve performance this collector assigns memory pools to each thread to let threads allocate new memory blocks without having to coordinate with other threads.
[src:gtk-sharp/mono-software] Migration of objects from the nursery to the old generation is done by copying the data from the nursery to the old generation pool and updating any live pointers that point to the data to point to the new location.
[src:gtk-sharp/mono-software] This can be expensive for large objects, so Mono's SGen uses a separate pool of memory for large objects (Large Object Section) and uses a mark-and-sweep algorithm for those objects.
[src:gtk-sharp/mono-software] The *class library* provides a comprehensive set of facilities for application development.
[src:gtk-sharp/mono-software] They are primarily written in C#, but due to the Common Language Specification they can be used by any .NET language.
[src:gtk-sharp/mono-software] The class library is structured into namespaces, and deployed in shared libraries known as assemblies.
[src:gtk-sharp/mono-software] Speaking of the .NET Framework is primarily referring to this class library.
[src:gtk-sharp/mono-software] The Common Language Infrastructure (CLI) as implemented by the Common Language Runtime (CLR), is implemented by the Mono executable.
[src:gtk-sharp/mono-software] The runtime compiles and executes .NET applications.
[src:gtk-sharp/mono-software] The common language infrastructure is defined by the ECMA standard.
[src:gtk-sharp/mono-software] To run an application, you must invoke the runtime with the relevant parameters.
[src:gtk-sharp/mono-software] The *Common Language Specification* (CLS) is specified in chapter 6 of ECMA-335 and defines the interface to the CLI, such as conventions like the underlying types for Enum.
[src:gtk-sharp/mono-software] The Mono compiler generates an image that conforms to the CLS.
[src:gtk-sharp/mono-software] This is the Common Intermediate Language.
[src:gtk-sharp/mono-software] The Mono runtime takes this image and runs it.
[src:gtk-sharp/mono-software] The ECMA standard formally defines a library that conforms to the CLS as a framework.
[src:gtk-sharp/mono-software] Within a native .NET/Mono application, all code is managed; that is, it is governed by the CLI's style of memory management and thread safety.
[src:gtk-sharp/mono-software] Other .NET or Mono applications can use legacy code, which is referred to as unmanaged, by using the System.Runtime.InteropServices libraries to create C# bindings.
[src:gtk-sharp/mono-software] Many libraries which ship with Mono use this feature of the CLI, such as Gtk#.
[src:gtk-sharp/mono-software] In addition, Mono is available on a variety of operating systems and architectures.
[src:gtk-sharp/mono-software] Several projects extend Mono and allow developers to use it in their development environment.
[src:gtk-sharp/mono-software] Microsoft has a version of .NET 2.0 now available only for Windows XP, called the Shared Source CLI (Rotor).
[src:gtk-sharp/mono-software] Microsoft's shared source license may be insufficient for the needs of the community (it explicitly forbids commercial use).
[src:gtk-sharp/mono-software] Free Software Foundation's decommissioned Portable.NET project.
[src:gtk-sharp/mono-software] MonoDevelop is a free integrated development environment primarily designed for C# and other .NET languages such as Nemerle, Boo, and Java (via IKVM), although it also supports languages such as C, C++, Python, and Vala.
[src:gtk-sharp/mono-software] MonoDevelop was originally a port of SharpDevelop to Gtk#, but it has since evolved to meet the needs of Mono developers.
[src:gtk-sharp/mono-software] The IDE includes class management, built-in help, code completion, Stetic (a GUI designer), project support, and an integrated debugger.
[src:gtk-sharp/mono-software] The MonoDoc browser provides access to API documentation and code samples.
[src:gtk-sharp/mono-software] The documentation browser uses wiki-style content management, allowing developers to edit and improve the documentation.
[src:gtk-sharp/mono-software] Xamarin.iOS and Xamarin.Android, both developed by Xamarin, were implementations of Mono for iPhone and Android-based smartphones.
[src:gtk-sharp/mono-software] Previously available only for commercial licensing, after Microsoft's acquisition of Xamarin in 2016, the Mono runtime itself was relicensed under MIT license and both Xamarin.iOS and Xamarin.Android are being made free and open-source.
[src:gtk-sharp/mono-software] Xamarin.iOS and Xamarin.Android reached end-of-life on May 1, 2024, being integrated directly into .NET.
[src:gtk-sharp/mono-software] Microsoft recommends migration to .NET MAUI.
[src:gtk-sharp/mono-software] Xamarin.iOS (previously named MonoTouch) was a library that allows developers to create C# and .NET based applications that run on the iPhone, iPod and iPad devices.
[src:gtk-sharp/mono-software] It was based on the Mono framework and developed in conjunction with Novell.
[src:gtk-sharp/mono-software] Unlike Mono applications, Xamarin.iOS "Apps" were compiled down to machine code targeted specifically at the Apple iPhone and iPad.
[src:gtk-sharp/mono-software] This is necessary because the iOS kernel prevents just-in-time compilers from executing on the device.
[src:gtk-sharp/mono-software] Xamarin Studio was used as the primary IDE, however additional links to Xcode and the iOS simulator have been written.
[src:gtk-sharp/mono-software] From April to early September 2010, the future of MonoTouch was put in doubt as Apple introduced new terms for iPhone developers that prohibited them from developing in languages other than C, C++ and Objective-C, and the use of a middle layer between the iOS platform and iPhone applications.
[src:gtk-sharp/mono-software] This made the future of MonoTouch, and other technologies such as Unity, uncertain.
[src:gtk-sharp/mono-software] Then, in September 2010, Apple rescinded this restriction, stating that they were relaxing the language restrictions that they had put in place earlier that year.
[src:gtk-sharp/mono-software] Xamarin.Android (formerly known as Mono for Android), initially developed by Novell and continued by Xamarin, was a proprietary implementation of Mono for Android-based smart-phones.
[src:gtk-sharp/mono-software] Mono for Android was developed to allow developers to more easily write cross-platform applications that will run on all mobile platforms.
[src:gtk-sharp/mono-software] In August 2010, a Microsoft spokesman, Tom Hanrahan of Microsoft's Open Source Technology Centre, stated, in reference to the lawsuit filed by Oracle against Google over Android's use of Java, that "The type of action Oracle is taking against Google over Java is not going to happen.
[src:gtk-sharp/mono-software] Cocoa# (also known as CocoaSharp) was a bridge framework for Mac OS X, which allowed applications developed with the Mono runtime to access the Cocoa API.
[src:gtk-sharp/mono-software] It was initially released on August 12, 2004, and was included with the Mono distribution starting with version 1.0.6, released on February 18, 2005.
[src:gtk-sharp/mono-software] It has not seen any development since 2008, and is now deprecated.
[src:gtk-sharp/mono-software] It allows .NET developers to use most of the Mac OS X API, including Cocoa, with no native code, while still achieving a native UI.
[src:gtk-sharp/mono-software] Xamarin.Mac is a library that allows developers to run .NET and C# apps on the Mac.
[src:gtk-sharp/mono-software] Mono is dual licensed by Xamarin, similar to other products such as Qt and the Mozilla Application Suite.
[src:gtk-sharp/mono-software] These are all free software and open-source licenses and hence Mono is free and open-source software.
[src:gtk-sharp/mono-software] On March 18, 2016, Microsoft's acquisition of Xamarin was officially closed.
[src:gtk-sharp/mono-software] On July 6, 2009, Microsoft announced that it was placing their ECMA 334 and ECMA 335 specifications under their Community Promise pledging that they would not assert their patents against anyone implementing, distributing, or using alternative implementations of .NET.
[src:gtk-sharp/mono-software] Mono's implementation of those components of the .NET stack not submitted to the ECMA for standardization has been the source of patent violation concerns for much of the life of the project.
[src:gtk-sharp/mono-software] In particular, discussion has taken place about whether Microsoft could destroy the Mono project through patent suits.
[src:gtk-sharp/mono-software] The base technologies submitted to the ECMA, and therefore also the Unix/GNOME-specific parts, are claimed to be safe due to Microsoft's explicitly placing both ECMA 334 (C#) and ECMA 335 (CLI) standards under the Microsoft Community Promise.
[src:gtk-sharp/mono-software] The concerns primarily relate to technologies developed by Microsoft on top of the .NET Framework, such as ASP.NET, ADO.NET and Windows Forms (see non-standardized namespaces), i.e. parts composing Mono's Windows compatibility stack.
[src:gtk-sharp/mono-software] These technologies are today not fully implemented in Mono and not required for developing Mono-applications, they are simply there for developers and users who need full compatibility with the Windows system.
[src:gtk-sharp/mono-software] The Free Software Foundation's Richard Stallman has stated on June 2, 2009, that "[...] we should discourage people from writing programs in C#.
[src:gtk-sharp/mono-software] Therefore, we should not include C# implementations in the default installation of GNU/Linux distributions or in their principal ways of installing GNOME".
[src:gtk-sharp/mono-software] Mono developer Joseph Michael Shields defended the performance of Banshee on ARM, and also the claims that Banshee was not well-maintained as being a "directed personal insult" to one of its major contributors.
[src:gtk-sharp/mono-software] Many programs covering a range of applications have been developed using the Mono application programming interface (API) and C#.
[src:gtk-sharp/mono-software] Some programs written for the Linux Desktop include Banshee, Beagle, F-Spot, Gbrainy, Docky/GNOME Do, MonoTorrent, Pinta, and Tomboy.
[src:gtk-sharp/mono-software] The program, Logos 5 Bible Study Software (OS X Version), was written for the MacOS.
[src:gtk-sharp/mono-software] A number of video games, such as *The Sims 3* and*Second Life* (for their scripting languages), OpenSimulator virtual world server, or games built with the Unity or MonoGame game engines, also make use of Mono.
[src:gtk-sharp/mono-software] OpenRA bundles its Apple Disk Image and Linux AppImages with Mono essentially removing almost all dependencies from the game.
